<AbstractNarration>DMS-0307078&lt;br/&gt;Adam Sikora&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Thirty years ago B. Mazur discovered some surprising &lt;br/&gt;similarities (a) between knots and prime numbers, and (b) between&lt;br/&gt;3-dimensional manifolds and number fields. Those similarities were&lt;br/&gt;further elaborated by Kapranov, Morishita, Ramachandran, Reznikov, and&lt;br/&gt;PI, but the full scope of these analogies is still unknown. &lt;br/&gt;PI's goal is to continue investigation of these analogies and their &lt;br/&gt;roots.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Arithmetic topology is an exiting new area of mathematical research&lt;br/&gt;relating two of the most active areas of mathematical research&lt;br/&gt;in the recent years: low-dimensional topology and number theory. &lt;br/&gt;The development of Arithmetic Topology is driven by the desire to &lt;br/&gt;establish&lt;br/&gt;rigorous and uniform foundations for those two seemingly diverse &lt;br/&gt;theories.</AbstractNarration>
